This is the final lesson of fout on slam bidding. To review, the first 2 lessons were on hand evaluation. They were the most important, as they apply to all auctions, partials, games, and slams. Just as a reminder. If you use Bergen's methods of hand evaluation, you ^*Ineed 26 points between the combined hands^*N to bid game. If you have 33 points or more, you are in the slam range.|
PG| ***** 79 ***** |


at|

However, just because you have 33 points, it does not mean you should automatically bid slam . You need to make sure you do not have two losers off the top. That means you have to have first round control (ace or void) of 3 suits, and 2nd round control (King or singleton) of the fourth suit.|
PG| ***** 80 ***** |


AT|

Control bids were the topic of the third lesson, last week. In that lesson, I discussed control bids and Roman Key Card Blackwood, which are used to make sure you have the necessary controls in all suits. So, we now have the theoretical foundation about what we need to bid slam, and how to stop if slam cannot be made. |
